ing of his theology. The collection will enrich contemporary public theological discussion, adding Niebuhr's confessionally grounded yet publicly focused voice to the conversation. Richard R. Niebuhr contributes a Foreword in which he recollects his father and offers insights from private writings, and William Stacy Johnson's Introduction orients the reader to Niebuhr's life and work, locating his writings in appropriate theological and historical contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aTheology. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / General.2bisacsh1 aJohnson, William Stacy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, William Stacy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNiebuhr, Richard R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030006370740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014711740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300147117423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300147117/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY